          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most networking fails because it is transactional — people reach out only when they need something and make little investment in genuine relationship-building. People can sense transactional intent, which creates resistance rather than connection. Effective networking is built on genuine curiosity, consistent giving, and long-term relationship investment." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are weak ties and why do they matter for career growth?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Weak ties are connections to people you know moderately well but do not interact with regularly — acquaintances, former colleagues, LinkedIn connections. Sociologist Mark Granovetter's research showed that most career opportunities come from weak ties, not close friends, because weak ties connect you to different networks with different information and opportunities." }
        },
